R Deep Dive with ggplot2

1 - Introduction - About R Notebooks

This is an R Markdown Notebook. When you execute code within the notebook, the results appear beneath the code. In R Markdown documents, code is embedded in chunks, marked off by three back ticks and then the designation {r}. You can add additional detail about the chunk after the r, i.e.setup, information about the calculation, etc. You can also specify if you want the code itself to be included in any output document (the echo option), and if you want any displayed results to be included (the eval option). By default both options are set to true, so both code and output will be included in any output. We will use code chunks throughout this document for examples, and you will also create your own code chunks.

How to run a code chunk

To execute a code chunk, click the Run button within the chunk (green arrow in the top right), or put your cursor inside the code chunk grey window and press Cmd+Shift+Enter.

Document organization using Markdown

Youll also notice that sections are marked off by hashmarks - #. This provides formatting when publishing this document as a PDF, slideshow, etc. It also allows for navigation via the navigation bar at the bottom of this document window. You can navigate throughout the document using the menu.

Saving and previewing the notebook

When you save the notebook, an HTML file containing the code and output will be saved alongside it. Click the Preview button or press Cmd+Shift+K to preview the HTML file - this will appear in the right hand side window in the Viewer tab. The preview shows you a rendered HTML copy of the contents of the editor. Consequently, unlike Knit, Preview does not run any R code chunks. Instead, the output of the chunk when it was last run in the editor is displayed.

3 - Simple Scatter Plot

Theres lots of data that we can play with here. Lets start by making a simple plot of atomic mass versus atomic number to check the integrity of our data. What should this plot look like? Run the code below to generate a graph.

ggplot(data=periodicTable, aes(x=numb,y=mass)) + geom_point()

This is an example of the most basic of ggplots. It has three key elements:

  1. data=: the data you are plotting (usually the name of your data frame in your environment)

  2. aes(): these are the aesthetic mappings for the plot - how we are visually representing the data variables. The basic ones used here are:
  • what data to plot on the x axis (x=vector_in_dataframe)
  • what data to plot on the y axis (y=vector_in_dataframe)
  1. An additional layer (signified by the + symbol) to describe what the plotted data should look like using the geom designation.

In this case, we are using the periodicTable dataframe, and plotting numb on x and mass on y. We are specifiying the data be represented as individual points.

Exercise 3.4 - Adding Color by Factor

Our previous plot shows us the variation, but it would be more accurate to have the periods as discrete colors and not a gradient. The reason it plotted period as a gradient is because in the data frame, period is an integer. ggplot treats number and integer vectors as continuous variables by default - hence it uses a gradient color scheme. In this case, we want period to be a categorical value, or a factor. This can be done by changing color=period to color=factor(period).

Add a new chunk by clicking the Insert Chunk button (top of the window on the toolbar) or by pressing Cmd+Option+I. Make this modification - color=factor(period) - and replot. (Watch your parenthesis!)

Insert chunk here :)

Alternately, to get the same effect, you can change the data type for that column directly in the data frame. You can do that with the following command (you dont need to run this):

periodicTable$period <- factor(periodicTable$period)

Then, when you add color=period, ggplot will automatically plot it as a factor.

However, if youre not sure you want to permanently change a data type, just modify it in the ggplot expression.

You can change the type back to numberic with the following (also, you dont need to run this):

periodicTable$period <- as.numeric(periodicTable$period)

Its tricker to change it back to the original integer type, but more information on that can be found here: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/3418128/how-to-convert-a-factor-to-integer-numeric-without-loss-of-information

4 - Adding a Fit

Lets go back to our original graph of mass versus numb from the beginning of Section 3 (the section_3_mass_vs_numb chunk, if you are using the navigation menu at the bottom):

ggplot(data=periodicTable,aes(x=numb,y=mass)) + geom_point()

We would like to add a linear fit to this graph. We can do this by adding a layer of geom_smooth() and specifying the model we want to use. There are many options that can be used for a fit - more info on geom_smooth() can be found here: https://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/geom_smooth.html.

Insert chunk here :)

Exercise 4.2 - Adding linear fit parameters to the plot

It might be useful to display the parameters, like slope and intercept, of the fitted line on the graph. How can we do that? Although the plot is calculated by ggplot, we need to do the calculation for the fit parameters outside of ggplot in order to get the exact numbers. Then we can add them to the plot.

The following code runs a simple linear model approximation on our data (lm), stores it in an object called mass_correlation, and displays the slope and intercept values of the line we generated above. lm is a function contained in the stats package, which is included in the standard installation of R.

Run the code below. Do the numbers make sense?

mass_correlation <- lm(mass ~ numb, data=periodicTable)
coef(summary(mass_correlation))
             Estimate  Std. Error   t value      Pr(>|t|)
(Intercept) -9.004058 0.666401668 -13.51146  1.714181e-25
numb         2.613775 0.009928983 263.24703 9.504291e-162

We can pull out the specific correlation values using the following indices - run the code below to assign these values to objects called intercept and slope:

intercept <- mass_correlation$coefficients[1]
slope <- mass_correlation$coefficients[2]
intercept
(Intercept) 
  -9.004058 
slope
    numb 
2.613775

Since we are focusing on plotting here and not on statistics, lets figure out how to get this on our plot. Believe it or not this is not as straightforward as one might think. Text is added to plots using an annotate() layer. More info on annotate() can be found here: https://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/annotate.html.

The options for annotate() include the type of annotation (in this case text), the position on the graph (x and y values), and the value (this can be a reference to a value in a vector, dataframe or list, indicated by label=).

Run the code below to show how to add a text annotation for the intercept value to the plot:

ggplot(data=periodicTable,aes(x=numb,y=mass)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method="lm") + annotate("text", x=10, y=200, label=intercept)

Lets add the slope value to the graph now. Add a new chunk by clicking the Insert Chunk button (top of the window on the toolbar) or by pressing Cmd+Option+I. Copy the code from the section_4_2-add_annotation chunk above and add a second annotate() layer to add the value for the slope. You may need to adjust your x and y values!

Exercise 4.3 - Customizing annotations

It would be nice to describe what those values are on the plot. There are ways to add more text (i.e.label the values for the slope and intercept). You can combine text and calculated values using the paste() command in your label, i.e. paste("Intercept = ", intercept) and using this in the label option. Run the following code for an example:

ggplot(data=periodicTable,aes(x=numb,y=mass)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method="lm") + annotate("text", x=20, y=200, label=paste("Slope = ", slope))

Lets add the equation for the line to the graph. Add a new chunk by clicking the Insert Chunk button (top of the window on the toolbar) or by pressing Cmd+Option+I. Exercise 5.2 - Customizing Axes Position

What would make this plot look a little better?

We can rotate the X-axis label text using a theme() layer. The theme() layer is where all the non-content (i.e.non-data) elements of our graphs live. There are tons of options for themes (use help -> theme), and also many pre-defined themes.

Lets replot our graph and make it a little easier to read. Add a new chunk by clicking the Insert Chunk button (top of the window on the toolbar) or by pressing Cmd+Option+I. To make our text a little easier to read, add the following layer to the graph:

  • theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=90,hjust=1,vjust=0.5))

The element_text command will change the angle, hjust (horizontal justification/position) and vjust (vertical justification/position) for the text of the X axis element (axis.text.x).

Exercise 5.3 - Assigning a Plot to an Object for Reuse

Lets say you want to experiment with a few different label types, but do not want to have to re-type the entire ggplot command every time you make your graph. At any point, with any number of layers, a ggplot can be assigned to an object, and that object can then be called and modified with further layers.

Run the following code chunk to assign our element type plot, without label modifications, to an object called et. The code will then display the et object.

et <- ggplot(data=periodicTable) + geom_bar(mapping=aes(x=type)) + labs(x="Element Type", y="Number of Elements", title="Numbers of Elements by Type")
et

You can see now that a new object, et, is available in the Global Environment, and you can inspect the additional plotting parameters that are stored in there. Why is this important? You may have a situation where you will be working with the same basic plot type over and over again - this gives you a programmatic way to modify aspects of the graph without retyping (or copy/pasting) the entire command. In general, for reproducible analysis, using objects is highly recommended.

Now, if we want to add a theme layer to our base et plot, we can simply run: et + theme()

Add a new chunk by clicking the Insert Chunk button (top of the window on the toolbar) or by pressing Cmd+Option+I. Recreate our element type plot using the et object, but rotate the X axis text 45 degrees.

6 - Three-Dimensional Plots: Periodic Table Trends

We know that there are trends that we can see in the periodic table. This is an example of three-dimensional data. We have the two dimensions of the table - row and column - and our third dimension is the property that varies with them. Examples of this variance can be seen in ionic radius, electronegativity, etc.

Lets make a plot of the periodic table that will show some of these trends. Run the code below to create a plot of the periodic table showing variance of electronegativiy with table position. The main layer creates the table, with X being the column and Y being the row. One type of 3D plot is geom_tile, and the aesthetic that we tell it to fill with is the Eneg (electronegativity) value (the z direction). So we should expect to see a color variance (what type of vector is Eneg?) with position in X and Y.

ggplot(data=periodicTable,aes(x=col,y=row)) + geom_tile(aes(fill=Eneg))

Exercise 6.1 - Manipulating Axes

So this looks close - what do we need to do to fix this?

Lets start by flipping the Y-axis. Add a new chunk by clicking the Insert Chunk button (top of the window on the toolbar) or by pressing Cmd+Option+I. Add the following line: + scale_y_reverse

Looks better!

Once you are happy with your plot, you can save it using the ggsave() command. There are other ways that offer more options, but this is one of the simplest and most common. It defaults to saving the last plot that was created. Run the following code to save your last plot to a jpeg file in your working directory:

ggsave("ptplot.jpeg")

By default ggsave identifies the file type (or device) based on the filename extension. You can specify a number of different file types by specifying the file type extension in your filename - i.e.ptplot.tiff, ptplot.pdf, etc. You can also specify width, height, and units of measure. More detail can be found on the https://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/ggsave.html.
